{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778292334,"nonce":"x63vxb1UDwc5NyIQMAdY/7/p9RA=","message":"**Why this came up now:** the 2026-05-09 baseline 2x2x2 matrix (architecture x smoothness x jerk; results comment ecfecc4 on efc4d68) showed within-condition pairwise RMSE on post-go forward velocity profiles still does not collapse to a discriminable level (best ratio 0.76 at GRU/jerk; we want \u003c 0.5). Low-rank recurrent constraint surfaced as a documented escalation candidate (training-methods coord c99ad9d).\n\n**Why we are not pursuing it now:** Michaels et al. 2020 (PNAS modular grasping), Shahbazi/Codol/Michaels/Gribble 2025 (savings paper), and Sussillo et al. 2015 all train delayed-reach RNN motor controllers WITHOUT a low-rank constraint. Mastrogiuseppe \u0026 Ostojic 2018 / Beiran 2021 / Dubreuil 2022 use low-rank specifically for decision-making, working memory, and contextual DM tasks — not motor control. There is no published precedent suggesting we need it for the kind of replicate-variance issue we are facing, and other groups appear to converge full-rank GRU/RNN reach controllers without resort to low-rank. Implementation cost is also non-trivial (custom LowRankGRUCell in feedbax).\n\n**Status:** keep deferred. Revisit only after exhausting all other escalation steps (smoothness, jerk, activity L2 sweep, vRNN tau-sweep `32efb6f`, longer warmup). The empirical rank-ablation issue `cf56e1e` (rank-1 -\u003e full GRU under matched adversary, in the f695729 phase chain) probes the same dimension question without imposing the constraint during training, and is the cheaper way to get evidence on whether rank actually matters here.","files":null}]}